{{pagebanner|caption=The magnificent Gare do Oriente (Lisbon Oriente Station), designed by Spanish architect Santiago Calatrava.}}

'''Parque das Nações''' is a district in [[Lisbon]], [[Portugal]]. The "Park of the Nations" was built from scratch for  Expo '98 (1998 Lisbon World Exposition) in the northeastern end of Lisbon. After the Expo, many of the impressive constructions and decorations were kept, while new residential, commercial, and office buildings were added to form a thriving, mixed-use district consisting exclusively of modern architecture and making the most of its river-facing location by offering a number of leisure facilities.

== Get in ==
{{mapframe | 38.755 | -9.120 | height=650 | width=500 | zoom=13 }} 
{{mapshapes|Q746032}}
{{mapshape|wikidata=Q686717, Q1786435, Q1428475|stroke-width=0}}

Metro line {{rint|lisbon|vermelha}} ("red", though it's pink on signage) runs cross-town to Parque das Nações, Oriente railway and bus station, and the airport. From the historic centre take the green line north and change at Alameda. 

{{marker | name=Gare do Oriente | type=go | wikidata=Q801115 }} is Lisbon's principal transport hub, designed by Santiago Calatrava for Expo '98. All trains and buses call here, though some trains start downtown at Santa Apolónia. Level 0 is the plaza through the building's main arch. Level 1 has ticket kiosks and machines plus cafes and Level 2 has the platforms. Level -1 is retail, Level -2 is the Metro station with platforms on Level -3. 

The taxi rank is west side, then the bus stands are just beyond. Not much here apart from the stands, as you use the facilities in the main building. No timetables, ticketing or departure info, again use the main building. 

